-- Equities in South Africa Breach 30,000; Anglo, Avusa, Billiton Are Active
-- B y   R o n   D e r b y
-- 2010-10-13T11:58:50Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-13/equities-in-south-africa-breach-30-000-anglo-avusa-billiton-are-active.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  breached the 30,000 level for the first time since
July 2008, adding 396.08, or 1.3 percent, to 30,175.23 at 1:42
p.m. in Johannesburg trading, a fourth day of gains.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ) rose 8.70 rand, or 2.9 percent,
to 307.69 rand, its biggest intraday gain in a week. Copper
climbed to a 27-month high as demand prospects improved and the
dollar declined. Larger rival  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ) gained
4.87 rand, or 2.1 percent, to 237.15 rand.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s biggest miner of
the metal, rose 12.02 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 710 rand.
Platinum for immediate delivery climbed as much as 1.4 percent
to $1,702.25.  Impala Platinum Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-largest,
gained 3.79 rand, or 2 percent, to 194.29 rand, while  Lonmin Plc 
(LON SJ), the third-biggest, rose 3.08 rand, or 1.6 percent, to
196.68 rand.  Avusa Ltd.  (AVU SJ) gained 50 cents, or 2.3 percent, to
22.50 rand, reaching its highest level since Nov. 10, 2008.
 Mvelaphanda Group Ltd.  (MVG SJ), the investment holding company
that owns 25.5 percent of Avusa, said it may abstain from voting
on the company’s bid to buy Universal Print Group and Hirt &
Carter after trying to block the transaction, the Times
reported, citing an Mvelaphanda official that it didn’t
identify. Mvela rose by 1 cent, or 0.2 percent, to 5.18 rand.  Datatec Ltd.  (DTC SJ) climbed 42 cents, or 1.2 percent, to
34.92 rand. The information and communications technology
company’s profit for the six months through Aug. 31 surged 89
percent to $16.1 million compared with a year earlier.       Gold One International Ltd.  (GDO SJ) rose 22 cents, or 9.4
percent, to 2.57 rand, its highest intraday level since its
shares started trading in May last year. The bullion producer
said its African unit will own 73.9 percent of Goliath Gold, a
newly created company, according to a stock-exchange statement.  Mustek Ltd.  (MST SJ), the South African computer maker,
rose 10 cents, or 2.7 percent, to 3.80 rand, its biggest
increase since Sept. 27. The company, which owns 42 percent of
Comztek Holdings Ltd., is evaluating an offer from Datatec Ltd.
to acquire the unit.  -- Editors:  Ana Monteiro ,  Linda Shen .  To contact the reporter on this story:
